<article id="About">
   <h2>@ViewBag.Title</h2>
   <p>
      Home Scrum is a very simple project tracking tool that is loosely built around the Scrum methodology of software development.
      I am not sure this tool will ever completely implement all of the functionallity required to truly do scrum, so if you are
      looking for a full fledged scrum management tool, you probably need to keep looking.  This is meant to be a scrum-like tool
      for personal use (or very small groups).
   </p>
   <p>
      Home Scrum was started because I wanted a simple project I could work on in order to practice using some technologies
      that I do not get to use often at my day job.  These technologies include:
   </p>
   <ul>
      <li>MVC</li>
      <li>Object-Relational Mapping (I am using NHibernate in this project, though I have also used Microsoft's Entity Framework)</li>
      <li>Dependency Injection (I am using Ninject for this project, though I have also used Unity and MEF)</li>
   </ul>
   <p>
      I decided to go with this tool because I needed a way to keep track of tasks that I needed to do on these side projects I work on.
      I only get to work on them sporadically, so I am constantly forgetting where I am on the project and what needs to be done.  So I
      figured I may as well make one of the projects be the building of a tool to help me out.
   </p>
   <p>
      I named it "Home Scrum" because I suck at naming things, I am primarily going to use it for tracking projects that I work on
      at home in my spare time, and I didn't want to waste precious time (or brain cycles) coming up with a better name.
   </p>

